[1] China, H5N1 - vaccines
Date: Sat, 13 Mar 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: www.chinaview.cn, 12 Mar 2004 [edited]
<http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2004-03/12/content_1363400.htm>


Poultry vaccinated to prevent virus spread by migratory birds
---------------------------------------------------
The epidemic control headquarters of southwest China's Guizhou Province has
decided to vaccinate all poultry within 10 km of the Caohai Lake area to
prevent bird flu virus spread by migratory birds.

Migratory birds in frigid northwest China come to Caohai Lake every October
to survive winter and leave the area in April of the following year.

Located in the outskirts of Weining County town at an elevation of 2200
meters, the 45-sq-km Caohai is the largest natural freshwater lake in Guizhou.

Caohai is home to 184 kinds of birds including 7 rare species under top
government protection. Apart from the black-necked crane, the only plateau
crane left in the world, Caohai Lake hosted 514 common cranes, 1427
bar-headed geese, and 9750 ruddy shelduck this winter.

Though no cases of bird flu have been found in the region so far, the
provincial epidemic control headquarters is on high alert. It ordered a
thorough investigation of wild and domestic poultry at Caohai Lake.
Epidemic prevention workers are vaccinating poultry in designated areas and
disinfecting poultry pens.

