ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Obviously, recent Thai statements about regained HPAI-free status were
premature. In accordance with Article 2.1.14.2 of the OIE's Terrestrial
Animal Health Code, a country can consider itself free from HPAI 6 months
after the last infected flock is culled. For example, the Dutch Chief
Veterinary Officer informed the OIE on 11 Nov 2003 as follows: "The last
infected flock was culled on 11 May 2003. Since the above-mentioned last
infected flock, no other cases of HPAI have been recorded in the
Netherlands. In accordance with Article 2.1.14.2 of the Terrestrial Animal
Health Code, the Netherlands considers itself free from HPAI as from 11 Nov
2003". - Mod.AS]

[A recent newswire
<http://www.fchornet.com/vnews/display.v/ART/2004/03/10/4050d397c96e2> had
the following statement: "Economically, avian influenza will not be as
devastating to Asian economies as last year's SARS epidemic, analysts at
HDSC, a global bank, said. This is because poultry sales are not as
substantial to Asian countries' gross domestic product as revenue gained
from tourism." This suggests that the tourism tax revenue is higher than
an agricultural tax revenue. One suspects that Thailand, as the fourth
leading poultry exporter in the world, is very concerned, and does not have
sufficient funding to fully compensate the farmers affected by the outbreak
thereby creating a significant internal economic crisis. Hence a desire to
declare an HPAI-free status and resume poultry exports. - Mod.MPP]
